\topic{Basic Decay Concepts}
Three Basic Decay Types\footnote{See Krane 3.3, 6.1-6.5.}:
\begin{enumerate}
\item $\alpha$ decay:
Example: \ce{_{88}^{236} Ra \to ^{232}_{86} Rn + \alpha}, $KE_{\alpha} = 4.8$ MeV, $Q \to \lambda, t_{1/2} = 1600$ years. 
\item $\beta$ decay: \ce{n \to p^+ + e^- + \gamma}, Example: \ce{p^+ \to n + e^+ + \gamma}
\item $\gamma$ decay: \ce{X^* \to X}, excited state to lower Energy state.
\end{enumerate}

Decay mechanisms: $\lambda = -\frac{\dNdt}{N(t)} =$ decay constant, describe probability of decay per unit time. It is a constant for each decay. 
\begin{align}
\dNdt (t) &= - \lambda N(t) \\
N(t) &= N_0 e^{-\lambda  t} \\
N(t_{1/2}) &= \frac{1}{2} N(0) \\
t_{1/2} &= \frac{\ln 2}{\lambda} 
\end{align}

Decay Mode 1: Parent $N_1$ decay into daughter productor $N_2$: 
\begin{align}
N_1 (t) &= N_0 e^{-\lambda t} \\
N_2 (t) &= N_0 - N_1 (t) = N_0 (1 - e^{-\lambda t}) 
\end{align}

Decay Mode 2: Parent $N_1$ decay parallelly into daughters $N_{2,a}$ (with $\lambda_a$) and $N_{2,b}$ (with $\lambda_b$). The total decay constant is just $\lambda-t = \lambda_a + \lambda_b$. 
\begin{align}
N_1 (t) &= N_0 e^{-\lambda_t t} \\
N_{2,a} (t) &= \frac{\lambda_a}{\lambda_t} N_0 (1 - e^{-\lambda_t t}) \\
N_{2,b} (t) &= \frac{\lambda_b}{\lambda_t} N_0 (1 - e^{-\lambda_t t})
\end{align}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Alpha Decay %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\topic{Alpha Decay} \footnote{See Krane 8, Liboff 4.2 and 4.5 for more details}
\begin{itemize}
\item Why $\alpha$ decay occurs? Answer: Coulomb Repulsion Effect. Coulomb force increases super-linearly with respect to binding energy. There is a need to get rid of some protons. 

\item Concept of `Spontaneous Fission': spontaneous means some KE appears suddenly in the system for no apparent cause; it must be from the decrease in the mass of the system. It is in the form of: $A \to \frac{A}{2} + \frac{A}{2}$ with Q = 200 MeV. 
\item Why is the $\alpha$ particle chosen for spontaneously carrying away the positive charge?
    \begin{enumerate}
    \item  \ce{^4_2 He_2} is doubly magic, very stable, tightly bound structure;
    \item \ce{^4_2 He_2} has relatively small mass compared with the mass of its separate constituents (beats \ce{^{12} C}, \ce{^{18} O}). It is favored as an emitted particle if we hope to have the disintegration products as light as possible and thus get the largest possible release of KE. 
    \end{enumerate}
\item To determine whether a decay mode is possible, we need to check two things:
    \begin{enumerate}
    \item $Q > 0$. For instance, from Table~\ref{232-U}, for U-232, \ce{^4 H} is the only energetically possible decay mode. Decay through emission of lighter particles is not possible because they require energy instead of release energy;
    \item The disintegration constant for alpha emission cannot be too small, or say, the half-life must be less than $10^{16}$y. This is the reason why heavier particle emission is rarely observed: $\log t_{1/2} \propto \frac{1}{\sqrt{Q_{\alpha}}}$. $t_{1/2}$ is very sensitive to Q. Doubling Q may reduce the $t_{1/2}$ by a $10^{20}$ order of magnitude. Example, see Table~\ref{Th}. 
    \end{enumerate}
\end{itemize}
