\subtopic{Energies of alpha-decay}
Recall alpha decay process is \ce{^A_Z X_N \to ^4_2 He_2 + ^{A-4}_{Z-2} \Xp_{N-2}}. Apply Conservation of Energy:
\begin{align}
m_X c^2 &= m_{\Xp} c^2 + KE_{\Xp} + m_{\alpha} c^2 + KE_{\alpha} \\
(m_X - m_{\Xp} - m_{\alpha} ) c^2 &= KE_{\Xp} + KE_{\alpha} = Q \label{Q-alpha}\\
B(\Xp) + B(\alpha) - B(X) &= 0 \label{B-alpha} 
\end{align}
in which Eq~\ref{Q-alpha} is the net energy release in the decay (the total KE). The decay will occur spontaneously only if $Q >0$. 

Apply Conservation of Linear Momentum:
\begin{align}
0 &= P_{\Xp} - P_{\alpha} \\
P_{\Xp}^2 &= P_{\alpha}^2 \\
KE_{\Xp} m_{\Xp} &= KE_{\alpha} m_{\alpha} \\
KE_{\Xp} &= KE_{\alpha} \frac{m_{\alpha}}{m_{\Xp}} 
\end{align}
Together,
\begin{align}
Q &= KE_{\alpha} + KE_{\alpha} \frac{m_{\alpha}}{m_{\Xp}} \\
KE_{\alpha} &= \boxed{ Q \left( 1 - \frac{4}{A} \right) } \approx 98\% Q
\end{align}
That is, given $Q$, we can find $KE_{\alpha}$, and keep in mind that A is typically very large. Around 98\% of the Q goes into KE of the $\alpha$ particles, and only about 2\% goes into KE of the daughter particle (because it is heavy!), which comes out to be 100 keV typically. 

Having a large Q means the isotope is a strong $\alpha$ emitter. Typically we define a strong $\alpha$ emitter to have $A > 190$ 


\subtopic{Theory of alpha-emission}
Assumptions:
\begin{itemize}
\item The $\alpha$ particle is pre-formed: before emission it is held together with the daughter product; Assume the distance between the two is $a$. 
\item Within the volume of $r<a$, the interaction potential between the two is attractive; 
\item Outside, coulomb potential dominates which is repulsive. 
\end{itemize}
For $\alpha$ decay to happen, the energy available to the $\alpha$ particle has to be positive: $Q > 0$. There is a region from $r=a$ to $r=b$ that th maximum available KE, Q, is smaller than the Coulomb potential. Then the only possible way the wave can travel beyond this potential barrier is to quantum tunneling. 
\begin{align}
\mbox{Decay Constant } &=f \cdot P_T \\
f &= \frac{v_{\alpha}}{a} = \frac{v_{\alpha}}{1.25 A^{1/3}} 
\end{align}
If we plug in $V = -V_0 = -50 \MeV, Q_{\alpha} = 5 \MeV, KE_{\alpha} = Q - V = 55 \MeV = \frac{1}{2} m_{\alpha} V_{\alpha}^2$, we can find that $f = 5 \times 10^{21} \s^{-1}$, which is a higher frequency than nuclear vibration frequency (around $10^{12} \sim 10^{14} \s^{-1}$). 

Now we can consider the tunneling probability $P_T$ from $r$ to $r +\dr$. 
\begin{align}
P_T &= \frac{|e^{-k_2 (r+\dr)}|^2}{e^{-k_2 r}} = e^{-2 k_2 \dr} \\
k_2 &= \sqrt{\frac{2m(V (r) -Q)}{\hbar^2}} \\
\dP_T &= e^{-2k_2 (r) \dr} \\
P_T &= \prod_i \dP_{\tau} = \exp \left(-2 \int_a^b k_2 (r) \dr \right) = e^{-2 G}
\end{align}
in which $G = \int_a^b k_2 (r) \dr$ is the \textbf{Gamow Factor}. We are going to jump to the result of $G$: 
\begin{align}
G &= \int_a^b k_2 (r) \dr = \int_a^b \sqrt{\frac{2 \mu}{\hbar^2} \left( \frac{Z_{\alpha} Z_D e^2}{r} - Q_{\alpha} \right)} \dr \\
&= \sqrt{\frac{2 \mu}{\hbar^2 Q_{\alpha}}} (Z_{\alpha} Z_D e^2) \left[ \arccos \sqrt{x} - \sqrt{x(1-x)} \right] \\
&\xrightarrow{x = \frac{a}{b} < 1} \sqrt{\frac{2 \mu}{\hbar^2 Q_{\alpha}}} (Z_{\alpha} Z_D e^2) \left[ \frac{\pi}{2} - 2 \sqrt{x} \right]
\end{align}
in which $ x = \frac{a}{b} < 1$, and we can solve for $b$ for setting the potential to equal to the energy. 
\begin{align}
2G &= \sqrt{ 
\underbrace{ \left(\frac{2 \pi e^2 Z_{\alpha} Z_D}{\hbar c}\right)^2 \frac{\mu c^2}{2} }_{\mbox{Gamow Energy } E_G}
\frac{1}{Q}} \left[ 1 - \frac{4}{\pi} \sqrt{x} \right] \\
&= \sqrt{\frac{E_G}{Q}} \left[ 1 - \frac{4}{\pi} \sqrt{x} \right]
\end{align}

For \ce{^{238} U}, we calculate:
\begin{align}
\left[ 1 - \frac{4}{\pi} \sqrt{x} \right] &= 0.51 \\
E_G &= \left( \frac{2 \pi \times e^2 \times 2 \times 90}{197} \right)^2 \left( \frac{4 \times 234}{4 + 234} \times \frac{938}{2} \right) = 125,700 \MeV  \\
\sqrt{\frac{E_G}{Q}} &= \sqrt{ \frac{125700}{4.25} } = 172 \\
2 G &= 172 \times 0.51 = 88 \\
P_T &= e^{-88} = 6 \times 10^{-39} \\
\lambda_{\alpha} &= f \times P_T = 4 \times 10^{21} \s^{-1} \times 6 \times 10^{-39} \\
&= 2.4 \times 10^{-17} \s^{-1} \\
t_{1/2} &= \frac{0.693}{\lambda} = 3 \times 10^{16} \s = 10^9 \mbox{ yr} 
\end{align} 
Implications of Gamow's model:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Strong dependency on $Q$ because $E_G$ is so large. Recall the graph we had that doubling $Q$ results in a $10^{20}$ change in $t_{1/2}$. In fact, the modeled $E_G$ is a bit to large compared with measured values as see in Table~\ref{Q-t}. Another factor to take into account is that the $x = \frac{a}{b}$ term: as $A \up$, the spherical shape deforms, hence spherical approximation may not be all that accurate.
